<paragraph id="5802CB2C45956AD80CACAEC9CF14DA76" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3434CA9D8DC5C09BC6E500B40EBA77E3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="8E28EE8D1682717765F202BF817803AE" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Hoplopelidnota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hoplopelidnota candezei" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="candezei">
<emphasis id="5162063384BCB0C1BF98CD5ADFB3891E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hoplopelidnota candezei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
F. Bates, 1904.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="76A2CDE03691055748DB5B6580C5E096" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="species">
<paragraph id="F2D83FDDCD64144A391198C856C2BEF7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4476383AE01047C20ACEE0444C7335E5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1 species; length 19-24 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E7DE938E45EC5C34F09C44D55FA308CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName id="CBDCB07D56A3BDFE790418B0157DB7D5" authorityName="F. Bates" authorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Hoplopelidnota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hoplopelidnota" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9330DB727E02FB1FAE3E3F2215AD6DC4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hoplopelidnota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rarely found in collections. Similar to species of 
<taxonomicName id="9A90502AEA0829D9B6CA2702AB0F7AB0" authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1844" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Chalcoplethis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chalcoplethis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8DA0036D1A52784C955487162AF99DB1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Chalcoplethis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="503BA16BF646DED320180E0A9CB69B2C" authorityName="Solier" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Catoclastus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Catoclastus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="353496354B66C0456BF983073885AC7C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Catoclastus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it possesses metallic green, rugose elytra. Prior to this work, females were not associated with males. The elytral callus of the male possesses a well-developed spine (shared with the pelidnotine genus 
<taxonomicName id="63171F2EFD09B8137F0DA8037A8E6CCD" authorityName="Ohaus" authorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Mesomerodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesomerodon" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D1B208D84B6297686BEAC37473D87BC9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mesomerodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; lacking in females of both 
<taxonomicName id="4C8595AEFE808988E0D10CC0B92AF63F" authorityName="Ohaus" authorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Mesomerodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesomerodon" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AC737136AC4086CA5334981DF0CD68B0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mesomerodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6DAF698898F718B631568DA893D0E415" authorityName="F. Bates" authorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Hoplopelidnota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hoplopelidnota" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="94232F35DA6383A00217E1D862849DF2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hoplopelidnota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In addition to the spinose elytra, several unusual characters serve to diagnose the genus: fringe of setae produced beyond apex of elytra; metatibial apex straight (lacking a corbel); mesosternum produced beyond the mesometasternal suture; metasternum with two parallel, longitudinal furrows; pygidium of female with a well-developed horizontal ridge and weak discal concavity; terminal sternite in the female with two deep emarginations on either side of the apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="69869354C87A760CBD1EC82E437B5DA1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The genus includes one species, 
<taxonomicName id="DB9027945C4EE5B5FDCC7BC56DDFC5CE" baseAuthorityName="Laporte" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Hoplopelidnota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hoplopelidnota metallica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="1D167B5A398687AA7763AE48C6A72856" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hoplopelidnota metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Laporte), which has a turbulent nomenclatural history (see &quot;Annotated Catalog&quot;; 
<bibRefCitation id="D013A05F58B173E386FF3DE9A01DA6F7" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-67.3.377" author="Moore, MR" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="377 - 387" refId="B226" refString="Moore, MR, Jameson, ML, 2013. Taxonomic and nomenclatural changes in the pelidnotine scarabs (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Rutelinae: Rutelini). The Coleopterists Bulletin 67: 377 - 387, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-67.3.377" title="Taxonomic and nomenclatural changes in the pelidnotine scarabs (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Rutelinae: Rutelini)." url="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-67.3.377" volume="67" year="2013">Moore and Jameson 2013</bibRefCitation>
). No analyses have examined the relationships of the genus to other rutelines. 
<taxonomicName id="A8A19D8FA9AD9D5AA333272BF149C1B5" baseAuthorityName="Laporte" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Hoplopelidnota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hoplopelidnota metallica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="B67729D28CDF69D75FBF73D058CA73FD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hoplopelidnota metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in northern South America, and we provide country records for Brazil, Guyana, and Venezuela.
</paragraph>
